Architecture plan for issues #3-#12

Project shape
- Existing app is Vite + React + TypeScript with npm scripts for dev, build,
  preview, lint, and format.
- Keep the site as a single-page landing page assembled from section
  components in `src/App.tsx`; no router is needed for anchor navigation.
- Use Tailwind CSS for page styling once issue #3 lands. Retire most custom
  `App.css` styles as sections are converted to utility classes and shared
  primitives.

Module structure and file organization
- `src/main.tsx`: React bootstrap only.
- `src/App.tsx`: top-level page composition, importing layout, nav, and section
  modules.
- `src/index.css`: Tailwind directives, global CSS variables, base element
  styles, smooth scrolling, focus defaults, and any small global resets.
- `src/components/layout/Container.tsx`: width-constrained responsive wrapper.
- `src/components/layout/Section.tsx`: section shell with anchor id, spacing,
  optional visual variants, and accessible labelling hooks.
- `src/components/ui/Button.tsx`: reusable CTA/link button with variants and
  sizes.
- `src/components/NavBar.tsx`: sticky responsive navigation with desktop links,
  CTA, and mobile menu state.
- `src/sections/Hero.tsx`, `HowItWorks.tsx`, `Features.tsx`,
  `WhyFounders.tsx`, `FAQ.tsx`, `FinalCTA.tsx`: issue-owned landing page
  sections.
- `src/config/content.ts`: typed copy/config for nav links, CTA text, section
  copy, feature cards, SDLC steps, founder narrative, and FAQs.
- `src/config/env.ts`: build-time Vite env adapter for the CTA target.
- `.env.example`: documents `VITE_CTA_URL`.

Shared types
- Define content-facing types near the content module, for example `NavItem`,
  `CtaConfig`, `HeroContent`, `StepItem`, `FeatureItem`, `FaqItem`, and
  `SectionId`.
- Keep component prop types colocated with components unless reused across
  modules.
- Model anchor ids as a string literal union so nav links and section ids stay
  consistent at compile time.

Dependencies between issues
- #3 Tailwind tokens is the styling foundation for all visual work.
- #4 layout primitives depends on #3 and should establish the reusable page
  structure consumed by every later section.
- #5 content/env config can proceed after the base app is in place and should
  be used by #6-#12 to avoid hard-coded copy and CTA URLs.
- #6 nav depends on #3, #4, and benefits from #5 for links and CTA config.
- #7 hero depends on #3, #4, and #5 for visual tokens, layout, and copy/CTA.
- #8, #9, #10, #11, and #12 depend on #3/#4 and should consume #5 content.
- Final integration should ensure all anchor ids used by #6 exist in the
  corresponding section components.

Key design decisions
- Use Tailwind theme tokens for the corust.ai-inspired look: high-contrast
  neutral base, sharp typography, restrained accent colors, consistent section
  spacing, and responsive container widths.
- Keep UI primitives small and semantic. `Button` should support rendering as
  an anchor for CTAs; `Section` should own spacing and ids; `Container` should
  own horizontal rhythm.
- Prefer static typed content over inline literals inside presentation
  components so later copy changes do not require touching layout code.
- Read `import.meta.env.VITE_CTA_URL` through a tiny config layer with a
  sensible fallback, and document it in `.env.example`.
- Implement the FAQ accordion with native accessible controls or explicit ARIA
  state; no headless UI dependency is needed unless later complexity demands it.
- Keep the landing page lightweight: no routing, global state library, data
  fetching layer, or component framework beyond React and Tailwind.
